background_story: Addison was known for being overly self-critical and always ready to apologize, even when it wasn't her fault. She would often take the blame for things that went wrong, just to avoid conflict or make others feel better. Her friends and family admired her kindness, but also worried that she was too quick to shoulder the responsibility for everyone else's mistakes. One day, Addison's boss mistakenly blamed her for a project delay, and she immediately apologized, even though she had done nothing wrong. However, after some reflection, she realized that she didn't have to apologize for everything. She began to work on setting boundaries and asserting herself, learning that being confident and honest didn't mean being unkind. Addison's journey taught her that being an apologist wasn't always the best approach, and that sometimes, standing up for herself was the most important thing she could do.
